				<p>Ha Long Bay or Sapa? This is probably the most asked question by visitors to the north of Vietnam. Breathtaking ricefields landscapes or thousand of islands surrounded by emerald waters? Lucky you, we did both and here we are to help you out!</p><h2><strong>Price</strong></h2><p>When choosing between Ha Long Bay or Sapa you need to keep in mind how much money you want to spend. For both options, there are so many companies and different packages, but in general, Ha Long Bay is a more expensive experience.</p><p><strong>Sapa prices oscillate between 40$ to 75$ for a 1 night and 2 days trekking</strong>, including a homestay in a village. Group size goes from 2 to 6. For this price, you will only be able to do day-trips to Ha Long Bay. <strong>A 1 night and 2 days experience in Ha Long Bay will be around 80$ to 250$ depending on the cruise you choose.</strong></p><p><strong>What we picked:</strong> For Sapa, we chose <strong><a href="http://www.booking.com/hotel/vn/sapa-o-39-chau-sapa.html?aid=1535401&amp;no_rooms=1&amp;group_adults=1">Sapa O&#8217;Chau</a></strong>, since a friend highly recommended to us and they do sustainable employment for the people in the area, which is always a plus. We chose the tour called &#8220;Off the beaten track&#8221; as we don&#8217;t like touristic activities and we paid 60$ each. The price didn&#8217;t include transportation. You can get there by <a href="https://12go.asia/en/train/hanoi/sapa/?z=1511837&amp;sub_id=sapatrain"><strong>train</strong></a> or <strong><a href="https://12go.asia/en/bus/hanoi/sapa/?z=1511837&amp;sub_id=sapabus">bus</a></strong>, making the latter more affordable. We got a sleeper bus for a night ride and it was very comfortable (only 10$ per person).</p><p></p><p>Ha Long Bay is one of the &#8220;you get what you pay for&#8221; places. If you get a cheap one, you may end up in an awful boat with awful food, wishing the cruise finishes as soon as possible. Thus, we went <em>really </em>out of our budget and chose the package also called &#8220;<strong><a href="https://www.booking.com/hotel/vn/indochina-sails-halong-city.en.html?aid=1886866&amp;no_rooms=1&amp;group_adults=1">Off the beaten track</a></strong>&#8221; offered by <strong><a href="https://www.booking.com/hotel/vn/indochina-sails-halong-city.en.html?aid=1886866&amp;no_rooms=1&amp;group_adults=1" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Indochina Junk</a></strong> for 149$ per person. Important to note that most of the cruises sleep in Ha Long Bay, along with thousands of boats. Choosing that package we wanted to avoid the crowds- our cruise spent the night on Bai Tu Long Bay with only a few boats on the horizon. The boat was pretty good. The price included a VERY comfortable transportation in a private van to Ha Long Bay, which takes around 4 hours from Hanoi.</p><figure id="attachment_418" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-418" style="width: 859px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-418 size-full" src="https://itfeelsgoodtobelost.files.wordpress.com/2018/06/indochina-junk.png" alt="Ha Long Bay or Sapa?" width="859" height="552" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-418" class="wp-caption-text">Photo by: Indochina Junk</figcaption></figure><h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Price: easy win for Sapa</strong></h4><p style="text-align: center;"><strong> </strong></p><h2><strong>Experience</strong></h2><p>I think when choosing between Ha Long Bay or Sapa you need to be very clear about your expectations and what are you looking for.</p><p>For us, Sapa is one of the highlights of all our trips. Our guide and homestay were simply incredible. We learned so much about her village and tribe, the landscape was breathtaking and the food was authentic. Most importantly, we didn&#8217;t see a single tourist for 2 days. When we left Sapa, we felt like leaving our second home, but we were full of joy thanks to Xuan, our guide. The connection you create with the place and people during these 2 days of trekking is amazing. We felt really inspired by Xuan and energized to travel! FYI, You need to be aware that Sapa is famous for being overcrowded by tourists so you have to be careful if you want a similar experience!</p>					</div>
